What you’re describing—the “everyone thought something weird just happened” moment—is real. But it doesn’t mean you used some hidden technique; it means you created a highly convincing story around a sharp outcome.

A few normal mechanisms stack together:

* Salience + timing: a rare streak (four in a row) happened right after a very visible build-up. The brain links those.
* Social proof: everyone saw the same thing and reacted together, which amplifies the “this is special” feeling.
* Expectation framing: your pact, the hype, the call-out beforehand—all primed people to look for a standout moment.
* Narrative fill-in: when something surprising happens, people look for an explanation. “He’s got some trick” is an easy, memorable one.
* Authority bias: knowing your background makes the “there’s a method here” story more believable.

Even for him, that can feel like “something was done to me,” when it’s really:

a good performance + strong framing + a room that was primed to interpret it as meaningful.

There’s also a feedback loop: once people start believing “there’s something to this,” their confidence and focus can actually improve in the moment, which reinforces the story.

